# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ahrensburg-culture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] The archaeological site **Abri de la Madeleine** (Magdalene Shelter) is a rock shelter under an overhanging cliff situated near Tursac, in the Dordogne *département* of the Aquitaine région of southwestern France.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] It represents the type site of the Magdalenian culture of the Upper Paleolithic.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] The shelter was also occupied during the Middle Ages.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] The medieval castle of Petit Marsac stands on the top of the cliff just above the shelter.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] Édouard Lartet, financed and helped by the Englishman Henry Christy, were the first systematic excavators of the site, starting in 1863, and published their findings in 1875 under the name of the Age of the Reindeer ("L'âge du renne").
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] Objects that were found at the **la Madeleine** site are distributed among a number of museums, including the Muséum de Toulouse, the Musee des Antiquites Nationales, St.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] The Abri de la Madeleine is classified as a *Monument historique* since 1956.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/abri-de-la-madeleine] In 1979, the Abri de la Madeleine was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List as part of the *Prehistoric Sites and Decorated Caves of the Vézère Valley* because of its unique paleolithic artwork and archeological importance.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Acheulean tools were produced during the Lower Palaeolithic era across Africa and much of West Asia, South Asia, East Asia and Europe, and are typically found with *Homo erectus* remains.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] It is thought that Acheulean technologies first developed about 2 million years ago, derived from the more primitive Oldowan technology associated with *Homo habilis*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The Acheulean includes at least the early part of the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Its end is not well defined; if Sangoan (also known as Epi-Acheulean) is included, it may be taken to last until as late as 130,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In Europe and Western Asia, early Neanderthals utilized Acheulean technology, later transitioning to the more advanced Mousterian beginning around 320,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The type site for the Acheulean is Saint-Acheul, a suburb of Amiens, the capital of the Somme department in Picardy, where artifacts were found in 1859.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] John Frere is generally credited as being the first to suggest a very ancient date for Acheulean hand-axes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In 1797, he sent two examples to the Royal Academy in London from Hoxne in Suffolk.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] He had found them in prehistoric lake deposits along with the bones of extinct animals and concluded that they were made by people "who had not the use of metals" and that they belonged to a "very ancient period indeed, even beyond the present world".
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] His ideas were, however, ignored by his contemporaries, who subscribed to a pre-Darwinian view of human evolution.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Later, Jacques Boucher de Crèvecœur de Perthes, working between 1836 and 1846, collected further examples of hand-axes and fossilised animal bone from the gravel river terraces of the Somme near Abbeville in northern France.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Again, his theories attributing great antiquity to the finds were spurned by his colleagues, until one of de Perthes' main opponents, Marcel Jérôme Rigollot, began finding more tools near Saint Acheul.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Following visits to both Abbeville and Saint Acheul by the geologist Joseph Prestwich, the age of the tools was finally accepted.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In 1872, Louis Laurent Gabriel de Mortillet described the characteristic hand-axe tools as belonging to *L'Epoque de St Acheul*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The industry was renamed as the Acheulean in 1925.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Providing calendrical dates and ordered chronological sequences in the study of early stone tool manufacture is often accomplished through one or more geological techniques, such as radiometric dating, often potassium-argon dating, and magnetostratigraphy.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] From the Konso Formation of Ethiopia, Acheulean hand-axes are dated to about 1.5 million years ago using radiometric dating of deposits containing volcanic ashes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Acheulean tools in South Asia have also been found to be dated as far as 1.5 million years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] However, in 2003 examples of the Acheulean from the West Turkana region of Kenya were described which have been dated through the method of magnetostratigraphy to about 1.76 million years ago, and in 2023 finds from Ethiopia were reported dating to 1.95 million years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The earliest user of Acheulean tools may have been *Homo ergaster*, who first appeared about 1.8 million years ago (not all researchers use this formal name, and instead prefer to call these users *early Homo erectus*).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] However, it is impossible to know for sure whether *Homo ergaster* was the only maker of early Acheulean tools, since other hominin species, such as *Homo habilis*, also lived in East Africa at this time.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] From geological dating of sedimentary deposits, it appears that the Acheulean originated in Africa and spread to Asian, Middle Eastern, and European areas sometime between 1.5 million years ago and about 800 thousand years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In individual regions, this dating can be considerably refined; in Europe for example, it was thought that Acheulean methods did not reach the continent until around 500,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] However, more recent research demonstrated that hand-axes from Spain were made more than 900,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] It is therefore important not to see the Acheulean as a neatly defined period or one that happened as part of a clear sequence but as one tool-making technique that flourished especially well in early prehistory.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The enormous geographic spread of Acheulean techniques also makes the name unwieldy as it represents numerous regional variations on a similar theme.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The term Acheulean does not represent a common culture in the modern sense, rather it is a basic method for making stone tools that was shared across much of the Old World.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In Europe, the more advanced Mousterian utilizing the Levallois technique appeared around 320,000 years ago, and had displaced the Acheulean in Europe and the Middle East by around 125,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The Acheulean had also disappeared from Africa by this time.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The Acheulean may have lasted much later, until around 50,000 years ago in East Asia.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The Mode 1 industries created rough flake tools by hitting a suitable stone with a hammerstone.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The resulting flake that broke off would have a natural sharp edge for cutting and could afterwards be sharpened further by striking another smaller flake from the edge if necessary (known as "retouch").
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These early toolmakers may also have worked the stone they took the flake from (known as a core) to create chopper cores although there is some debate over whether these items were tools or just discarded cores.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Advanced, later Acheulean toolmakers supplemented stone-on-stone percussion by utilizing "soft hammer" percussion using bone, antler, or wood tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These type of hammers, compared to stone, yields more control over the shape of the finished tool, and can be used to resharpen blunted tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The oldest locality showing evidence of "soft hammer" percussion in Eurasia is the Boxgrove site in southern England, dating to around 480,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Soft hammer percussion may have emerged around the same time in Africa.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Unlike the earlier Mode 1 industries, it was the core that was prized over the flakes that came from it.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Another advance was that the Mode 2 tools were worked symmetrically and on both sides indicating greater care in the production of the final tool.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Mode 3 technology emerged towards the end of Acheulean dominance and involved the Levallois technique, most famously exploited by the Mousterian industry.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Transitional tool forms between the two are called Mousterian of Acheulean Tradition, or MTA types.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The long blades of the Upper Palaeolithic Mode 4 industries appeared long after the Acheulean was abandoned.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] As the period of Acheulean tool use is so vast, efforts have been made to classify various stages of it such as John Wymer's division into Early Acheulean, Middle Acheulean, Late Middle Acheulean and Late Acheulean for material from Britain.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These schemes are normally regional and their dating and interpretations vary.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In Africa, there is a distinct difference in the tools made before and after 600,000 years ago with the older group being thicker and less symmetric and the younger being more extensively trimmed.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The primary innovation associated with Acheulean hand-axes is that the stone was worked symmetrically and on both sides.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] For the latter reason, handaxes are, along with cleavers, bifacially worked tools that could be manufactured from the large flakes themselves or from prepared cores.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Tool types found in Acheulean assemblages include pointed, cordate, ovate, ficron, and bout-coupé hand-axes (referring to the shapes of the final tool), cleavers, retouched flakes, scrapers, and segmental chopping tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Materials used were determined by available local stone types; flint is most often associated with the tools but its use is concentrated in Western Europe; in Africa sedimentary and igneous rock such as mudstone and basalt were most widely used, for example.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Other source materials include chalcedony, quartzite, andesite, sandstone, chert, and shale.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Even relatively soft rock such as limestone could be exploited.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In all cases the toolmakers worked their handaxes close to the source of their raw materials, suggesting that the Acheulean was a set of skills passed between individual groups.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Some smaller tools were made from large flakes that had been struck from stone cores.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These flake tools and the distinctive waste flakes produced in Acheulean tool manufacture suggest a more considered technique, one that required the toolmaker to think one or two steps ahead during work that necessitated a clear sequence of steps to create perhaps several tools in one sitting.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] A hard hammerstone would first be used to rough out the shape of the tool from the stone by removing large flakes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These large flakes might be re-used to create tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The tool maker would work around the circumference of the remaining stone core, removing smaller flakes alternately from each face.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The scar created by the removal of the preceding flake would provide a striking platform for the removal of the next.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Misjudged blows or flaws in the material used could cause problems, but a skilled toolmaker could overcome them.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Once the roughout shape was created, a further phase of flaking was undertaken to make the tool thinner.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The thinning flakes were removed using a softer hammer, such as bone or antler.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The softer hammer required more careful preparation of the striking platform and this would be abraded using a coarse stone to ensure the hammer did not slide off when struck.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Final shaping was then applied to the usable cutting edge of the tool, again using fine removal of flakes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Some Acheulean tools were sharpened instead by the removal of a tranchet flake.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This was struck from the lateral edge of the hand-axe close to the intended cutting area, resulting in the removal of a flake running along (parallel to) the blade of the axe to create a neat and very sharp working edge.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This distinctive tranchet flake can be identified amongst flint-knapping debris at Acheulean sites.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Loren Eiseley calculated that Acheulean tools have an average useful cutting edge of 20 centimetres (8 inches), making them much more efficient than the 5 centimetres (2 inches) average of Oldowan tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] A wear analysis of handaxes from the 480,000 year old late Acheulean Boxgrove site in England found that they were primarily if not exclusively used for animal butchery, with no evidence for their use in woodworking or digging.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Alternative theories include a use for ovate hand-axes as a kind of hunting discus to be hurled at prey.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Puzzlingly, there are also examples of sites where hundreds of hand-axes, many impractically large and also apparently unused, have been found in close association together.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Sites such as Melka Kunturé in Ethiopia, Olorgesailie in Kenya, Isimila in Tanzania, and Kalambo Falls in Zambia have produced evidence that suggests Acheulean hand-axes might not always have had a functional purpose.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Recently, it has been suggested that the Acheulean tool users adopted the handaxe as a social artifact, meaning that it embodied something beyond its function of a butchery or wood cutting tool.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Knowing how to create and use these tools would have been a valuable skill and the more elaborate ones suggest that they played a role in their owners' identity and their interactions with others.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This would help explain the apparent over-sophistication of some examples which may represent a "historically accrued social significance".
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] One theory goes further and suggests that some special hand-axes were made and displayed by males in search of a mate, using a large, well-made hand-axe to demonstrate that they possessed sufficient strength and skill to pass on to their offspring.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Once they had attracted a female at a group gathering, it is suggested that they would discard their axes, perhaps explaining why so many are found together.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This popular sexual selection hypothesis is controversial due to the assumptions made about sexual selection among extinct organisms.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Stone knapping with limited digital dexterity makes the center of mass the required direction of flake removal.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Physics then dictates a circular or oval end pattern, similar to the handaxe, for a leftover core after flake production.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This would explain the abundance, wide distribution, proximity to source, consistent shape, and lack of actual use, of these artifacts.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] showing important sites of the Acheulean industry (clickable map).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The geographic distribution of Acheulean tools – and thus the peoples who made them – is often interpreted as being the result of palaeo-climatic and ecological factors, such as glaciation and the desertification of the Sahara Desert.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Acheulean stone tools have been found across the continent of Africa, save for the dense rainforest around the Congo River which is not thought to have been colonized by hominids until later.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] It is thought that from Africa their use spread north and east to Asia: from Anatolia, through the Arabian Peninsula, across modern day Iran and Pakistan, and into India, and beyond.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In Europe their users reached the Pannonian Basin and the western Mediterranean regions, modern day France, the Low Countries, western Germany, and southern and central Britain.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Areas further north did not see human occupation until much later, due to glaciation.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In Athirampakkam at Chennai in Tamil Nadu the Acheulean age started at 1.51 mya and it is also prior than North India and Europe.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Until the 1980s, it was thought that the humans who arrived in East Asia abandoned the hand-axe technology of their ancestors and adopted chopper tools instead.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] An apparent division between Acheulean and non-Acheulean tool industries was identified by Hallam L.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Movius, who drew the Movius Line across northern India to show where the traditions seemed to diverge.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Later finds of Acheulean tools at Chongokni in South Korea and also in Mongolia and China, however, cast doubt on the reliability of Movius's distinction.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Since then, a different division known as the Roe Line has been suggested.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] This runs across North Africa to Israel and thence to India, separating two different techniques used by Acheulean toolmakers.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] North and east of the Roe Line, Acheulean hand-axes were made directly from large stone nodules and cores; while, to the south and west, they were made from flakes struck from these nodules.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Possible Acheulean-like bifacial technologies have also been discussed in relation to the Arubo 1 site in General Tinio, Nueva Ecija, Philippines, where archaeologists recovered a proto-handaxe and bifacial cleaver made from locally sourced chert.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Pawlik noted that the proto-handaxe "would certainly be regarded as typical for the Early Acheulean" if found in regions traditionally associated with Acheulean industries.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The assemblage has been cited in broader discussions regarding the diversity of bifacial technologies in Southeast Asia and the limitations of strict interpretations of the Movius Line.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Most notably, however, it is *Homo ergaster* (sometimes called early *Homo erectus*), whose assemblages are almost exclusively Acheulean, who used the technique.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Later, the related species *Homo heidelbergensis* (the common ancestor of both Neanderthals and *Homo sapiens*) used it extensively.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Late Acheulean tools were still used by species derived from *H. erectus*, including *Homo sapiens idaltu* and early Neanderthals.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The symmetry of the hand-axes has been used to suggest that Acheulean tool users possessed the ability to use language; the parts of the brain connected with fine control and movement are located in the same region that controls speech.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The wider variety of tool types compared to earlier industries and their aesthetically as well as functionally pleasing form could indicate a higher intellectual level in Acheulean tool users than in earlier hominines.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Others argue that there is no correlation between spatial abilities in tool making and linguistic behaviour, and that language is not learned or conceived in the same manner as artefact manufacture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Lower Palaeolithic finds made in association with Acheulean hand-axes, such as the Venus of Berekhat Ram, have been used to argue for artistic expression amongst the tool users.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The incised elephant tibia from Bilzingsleben in Germany, and ochre finds from Kapthurin in Kenya and Duinefontein in South Africa, are sometimes cited as being some of the earliest examples of an aesthetic sensibility in human history.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] There are numerous other explanations put forward for the creation of these artefacts; however, evidence of human art did not become commonplace until around 50,000 years ago, after the emergence of modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The kill site at Boxgrove in England is another famous Acheulean site.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Up until the 1970s these kill sites, often at waterholes where animals would gather to drink, were interpreted as being where Acheulean tool users killed game, butchered their carcasses, and then discarded the tools they had used.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Since the advent of zooarchaeology, which has placed greater emphasis on studying animal bones from archaeological sites, this view has changed.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Many of the animals at these kill sites have been found to have been killed by other predator animals, so it is likely that humans of the period supplemented hunting with scavenging from already dead animals.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Excavations at the Bnot Ya'akov Bridge site, located along the Dead Sea rift in the southern Hula Valley of northern Israel, have revealed evidence of human habitation in the area from as early as 750,000 years ago.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Archaeologists from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem claim that the site provides evidence of "advanced human behavior" half a million years earlier than has previously been estimated.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Their report describes an Acheulean layer at the site in which numerous stone tools, animal bones, and plant remains have been found.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Azykh cave located in Azerbaijan is another site where Acheulean tools were found.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In 1968, a lower jaw of a new type of hominid was discovered in the fifth layer (so-called Acheulean layer) of the cave.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Specialists named this type "Azykhantropus".
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Only limited artefactual evidence survives of the users of Acheulean tools other than the stone tools themselves.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Cave sites were exploited for habitation, but the hunter-gatherers of the Palaeolithic also possibly built shelters such as those identified in connection with Acheulean tools at Grotte du Lazaret and Terra Amata near Nice in France.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] The presence of the shelters is inferred from large rocks at the sites, which may have been used to weigh down the bottoms of tent-like structures or serve as foundations for huts or windbreaks.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] These stones may have been naturally deposited.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] In any case, a flimsy wood or animal skin structure would leave few archaeological traces after so much time.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Fire was seemingly being exploited by *Homo ergaster*, and would have been a necessity in colonising colder Eurasia from Africa.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulean] Conclusive evidence of mastery over it this early is, however, difficult to find.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The **Acheulo-Yabrudian complex** is a complex of archaeological cultures in the Levant at the end of the Lower Palaeolithic.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] It follows the Acheulian and precedes the Mousterian.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] It is also called the **Mugharan Tradition** or the **Acheulo-Yabrudian Cultural Complex (AYCC)**.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The Acheulo-Yabrudian complex has three stone-tool traditions, chronologically: the Acheulo-Yabrudian, the Yabrudian and the Pre-Aurignacian or Amudian.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The Yabrudian tradition is dominated by thick scrapers shaped by steep Quina retouch; the Acheuleo-Yabrudian contains Yabrudian scrapers and handaxes; and the Pre-Aurignacian/Amudian is dominated by blades and blade-tools.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] Determining the age period for the Acheulo-Yabrudian has been difficult as its major excavations occurred in the 1930s and 1950s, before modern radiometric dating.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] The recently excavated Qesem and Tabun caves, however, suggest the oldest period is about 350 kyr and the most recent 200 kyr.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/acheulo-yabrudian-complex] This would make the Lower–Middle Palaeolithic transition rapid occurring at 215,000 BP within a 30,000 year period.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The Afontova Gora complex consists of multiple stratigraphic layers, of five or more campsites.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The campsites shows evidence of mammoth hunting and were likely the result of an eastward expansion of mammoth hunters.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The human fossils discovered at Afontova Gora, a male and a girl dated to 17,000~15,000 years BP, were stored in the Hermitage Museum.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Layer 3 from Afontova Gora II is the most significant: the layer produced the largest amount of cultural artefacts and is the layer where the human fossil remains were discovered.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Over 20,000 artefacts were discovered at layer 3: this layer produced over 450 tools and over 250 osseous artefacts (bone, antler, ivory).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The fossils of two distinct individuals were discovered in the initial excavations: the upper premolar of an 11-15 year-old child and the left radius, ulna, humerus, phalanx, and frontal bone of an adult.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The bodies of two individuals, known as *Afontova Gora 2* (AG2) and *Afontova Gora 3* (AG3) were discovered within the complex (the name Afontova Gora 1 refers to the remains of a canid).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The human fossil remains of *Afontova Gora 2* were discovered in the 1920s at Afontova Gora II and stored at the Hermitage Museum.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] In 2009, researchers visited the Hermitage Museum and extracted DNA from the humerus of *Afontova Gora 2*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Despite significant contamination, researchers succeeded in extracting low coverage genomes.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] DNA analysis confirmed that the individual was male.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The individual showed close genetic affinities to *Mal'ta 1* (Mal'ta boy).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] *Afontova Gora 2* also showed greater genetic affinity for the Karitiana people than for the Han Chinese.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Around 1.9-2.7% of the genome was Neanderthal in origin.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Afontova Gora 2 belong to the Y-DNA haplogroup Q1a1-F746, an uniparental genetic marker that is infrequently observed in modern populations.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] In 2014, more human fossil remains were discovered at Afontova Gora II during salvage excavation before the construction of a new bridge over the Yenesei River.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The remains belonged to two different females: the atlas of an adult female and the mandible and five lower teeth of a teenage girl (*Afontova Gora 3*) estimated to be around 14–15 years old.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Initially, the new findings were presumed to be roughly contemporaneous with *Afontova Gora 2*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] In 2017, direct AMS dating revealed that *Afontova Gora 3* is dated to around 16,090 cal BC).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The mandible of *Afontova Gora 3* was described as being gracile.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Researchers analyzing the dental morphology of *Afontova Gora 3* concluded that the teeth showed distinct characteristics with most similarities to another fossil (the Listvenka child) from the Altai-Sayan region and were neither western nor eastern.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] *Afontova Gora 3* and Listvenka showed distinct dental characteristics that were also different from other Siberian fossils, including those from Mal'ta.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] DNA was extracted from one of the teeth of *Afontova Gora 3* and analyzed.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Compared to *Afontova Gora 2*, researchers were able to obtain higher coverage genomes from *Afontova Gora 3*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] DNA analysis confirmed that the individual was female. mtDNA analysis revealed that *Afontova Gora 3* belonged to the mitochondrial Haplogroup R1b.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Around 2.9-3.7% of the genome was Neanderthal in origin.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] In a 2016 study, researchers determined that *Afontova Gora 2*, *Afontova Gora 3*, and *Mal'ta 1* (Mal'ta boy) shared common descent and were clustered together in a *Mal'ta cluster*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Genetically, *Afontova Gora 3* is not closer to *Afontova Gora 2* when compared to *Mal'ta 1*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] When compared to *Mal'ta 1*, the *Afontova Gora 3* lineage apparently contributed more to modern humans and is genetically closer to Native Americans.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] Phenotypic analysis shows that *Afontova Gora 3* carries the derived rs12821256 allele associated with, and likely causal for, blond hair color, making *Afontova Gora 3* the earliest individual known to carry this derived allele.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The allele was found in three later members of the largely ANE-derived Eastern Hunter-Gatherers populations from Samara, Motala and Ukraine c.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] 10,000 BP, suggesting that it originated in the Ancient North Eurasian population before spreading to western Eurasia.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] A 2021 genetic study on the Tarim mummies found that they were primarily descended from a population represented by the *Afontova Gora 3* specimen (AG3), genetically displaying "high affinity" with it.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The genetic profile of the *Afontova Gora 3* individual represented about 72% of the ancestry of the Tarim mummies, while the remaining 28% of their ancestry was derived from Baikal EBA (Early Bronze Age Baikal populations).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] The Tarim mummies are thus one of the rare Holocene populations who derive most of their ancestry from the Ancient North Eurasians (ANE, specifically the Mal'ta and Afontova Gora populations), despite their distance in time (around 14,000 years).
[src:ahrensburg-culture/afontova-gora] More than any other ancient populations, they can be considered as "the best representatives" of the Ancient North Eurasians.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The **Ahmarian culture** was a Paleolithic archeological industry in the Levant dated at 46,000–42,000 years before present (BP) and thought to be related to Levantine Emiran and younger European Aurignacian cultures.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The word "Ahmarian" was adopted from the archaeological site of Erq el-Ahmar (also written Erk el Ahmar), West Bank, Palestine, a rockshelter in the Judean Desert in the northern Dead Sea Rift.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] It was explored and excavated by French Prehistorian René Neuville in 1951.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The "Ahmarian" category had only been recognized since the 1980s, and was previously designated as "Phase II Upper Paleolithic" or "Ksar Akil Phase B".
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The Ahmarian period together with the Emiran period, both from the Levant, are among the first periods of the Upper Paleolithic, corresponding to the first stages of the expansion of *Homo sapiens* out of Africa.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] From this stage, another wave of modern humans migrated to Europe from Africa to form the beginning of the European Upper Paleolithic, including the Aurignacian culture, where they become known as the Cro-Magnons.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The European Bohunician culture, may slightly predate the Ahmarian at 48,000 BP.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] There is also a claim that it is roughly contemporary with the Aurignacian and the Gravettian cultures of Europe, all emerging prior to the Atlitian, which was also contemporary with the Solutrean and Magdalenian cultures of Western Europe.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] Ahmarian technology, which included the complex of blade/bladelet-knapping techniques is also linked to the tools used by the hunter-gatherers of southwestern Asia.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] Ahmarian blades are usually elongated with some curves.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The Levallois technique is still in use, but only sparsely, thereby making Ahmarian the first fully Upper Paleolithic period.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] Ahmarian assemblages can be found throughout the Levant, including Syria, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine, and Jordan.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] The Lagaman industry in the Sinai can be considered as derivative to the Ahmarian culture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahmarian] "Levantine Aurignacian", from the Levant, is a type of blade technology very similar to the European Aurignacian, immediately following chronologically the Emiran and Early Ahmarian in the same area of the Near East, and closely related to them.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The **Ahrensburg culture** or **Ahrensburgian** (c.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] 12,900 to 11,700 BP) was a late Upper Paleolithic nomadic hunter culture (or technocomplex) in north-central Europe during the Younger Dryas, the last spell of cold at the end of the Weichsel glaciation resulting in deforestation and the formation of a tundra with bushy arctic white birch and rowan.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Some skeletons of reindeer have flint arrow tips in them, showing that the culture mastered the use of bows and arrows.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Ahrensburgian was preceded by the Hamburg and Federmesser cultures and superseded by the Maglemosian and Swiderian cultures.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Ahrensburgian finds were made in southern and western Scandinavia, the North German plain and western Poland.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Ahrensburgian area also included vast stretches of land now at the bottom of the North and Baltic Sea, since during the Younger Dryas the coastline took a much more northern course than today.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The culture is named after a tunnel valley near the town of Ahrensburg, 25 km (16 mi) northeast of Hamburg in the German state of Schleswig-Holstein, where Ahrensburg find layers were excavated in Meiendorf, Stellmoor and Borneck.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] While these as well as the majority of other find sites date to the Young Dryas, the Ahrensburgian find layer in Alt Duvenstedt has been dated to the very late Allerød, thus possibly representing an early stage of Ahrensburgian which might have corresponded to the Bromme culture in the north.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Artefacts with tanged points are found associated with both the Bromme and the Ahrensburg cultures.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The culture reached as far north as the Isles of Orkney in northern Scotland.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Ahrensburg culture belongs to a Late Paleolithic and early Mesolithic (or Epipaleolithic) cultural complex that started with the glacial recession and the subsequent disintegration of Late Palaeolithic cultures between 15,000 and 10,000 BCE.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The extinction of mammoth and other megafauna provided for an incentive to exploit other forms of subsistence that included maritime resources.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Northward migrations coincided with the warm Bølling and Allerød events, but much of northern Eurasia remained inhabited during the Younger Dryas.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] During the holocene climatic optimum, the increased biomass led to a marked intensification in foraging by all groups, the development of inter-group contacts, and ultimately, the initiation of agriculture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The different technolithic complexes are chronologically associated with the climatic chronozones.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The re-colonisation of Northern Germany is connected to the onset of the late Glacial Interstadial between Weichsel and the Dryas I glaciation, at the beginning of the Meiendorf Interstadial around 12,700 BCE.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Palynological results demonstrate a close connection between the prominent temperature rise at the beginning of the Interstadial and the expansion of the hunter-gatherers into the northern Lowlands.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The existence of a primary “pioneer phase” in the re-colonisation is contradicted by proof of e.g. an early Central European Magdalenian in Poland.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Today it is commonly accepted that the Hamburgian, featured by *"Shouldered Point"* lithics, is a techno-complex closely related to the Creswellian and rooted in the Magdalenian.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Within the Hamburgian techno-complex, a younger dating is found for the Havelte phase, sometimes interpreted as a northwestern phenomenon, perhaps oriented towards the former coastline.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Hamburgian culture existed during the warm Bølling period, the brief Dryas II glaciation (lasting 300 years) and in the early warmer Allerød period.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] However, the distribution of the Hamburgian east of the Oder River has been confirmed and Hamburgian culture can also be distinguished in Lithuania.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Finds in Jutland indicates the expansion of early Hamburgian hunters and gatherers reached further north than previously expected.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Hamburgian sites with shouldered point lithics reach as far north as the Pomeranian ice margin.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The younger Havelte phase has been proven for the area beyond the Pomeranian ice margin and on the Danish Isles after c.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The "Backed Point" lithics of Federmesser culture are usually dated in the Allerød Interstadial.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Early Federmesser finds follows shortly or are contemporary to Havelte.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The culture lasted approximately 1200 years from 11,900 to 10,700 BCE., and is located in Northern Germany and Poland to south Lithuania.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Fish-hooks were discovered in Allerød layers and emphasize the importance of fishing in the Late Palaeolithic.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] A certain survival of late Upper Palaeolithic traditions similar to contemporary Azilian (France, Spain) becomes apparent, such as the amber elk from Weitsche that can be considered as a link to the Mesolithic, amber animal sculptures.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Bromme culture sites are found in the entire southern and southeastern Baltic, and are dated to the second half of Allerød and the early cold Dryas III period.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The "classical" Brommian complex is typified by simple and fast, but uneconomical, flint processing using unipolar (single-platform) cores.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] A new development noticed in Lithuania introduced both massive and smaller *"tanged Points"*.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] In Bromme culture this technology is proposed to be an innovation derived from tanged Havelte groups.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] As such, derivation of Bromme culture and even migration of its representatives from the territories of Denmark and northern Germany have been proposed, although other sources hold early Bromme not to be very well defined in (late Allerød) Northern Germany, where it groups with Federmesser.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Ahrensburg culture is normally associated with the Younger Dryas glacialization and the Pre-boreal period.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Some recent finds, such as the Hintersee 24 site in southern *Landkreis* Vorpommern-Greifswald, would contribute to the argument of an early Ahrensburgian in northern Germany.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Alternatively, flint artefacts of Bromme tanged-point groups is considered to prelude the techno-complex of the Ahrensburg culture and would point to the provenience of Ahrensburg from Bromme culture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] As such, the Grensk culture in Bromme territory at the source of the Dnieper River was proposed to be the direct originator of Ahrensburgian culture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] However, the exact typological chronology of this culture is still unclear.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Though associated with the Bromme complex, Grensk culture has its roots more defined in the local Mammoth Hunters' culture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Another possibility derives from the observation that on a regional scale, the Hamburgian culture is succeeded geographically as well as chronologically by the Federmesser culture, or Arch-Backed Piece Complex.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The existence of a genuine Federmesser occupation in southern Scandinavia is highly controversial, and there is wide, though not unanimous, agreement that some Federmesser types constitute an integral part of the early Brommean artefact inventory.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Still, Federmesser types are also often found in close association with Hamburgian assemblages (e.g. at Slotseng and Sølbjerg) and tentative, dating from northern Germany shows some degree of contemporaneity between the late Hamburgian Havelte sites and the Federmesser ones.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Therefore, in southern Scandinavia the Federmesser may represent a brief transitory phase between the Hamburgian and the Brommean.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] This corresponds with the notion that "tanged point cultures" such as "Brommian" or "Bromme-Lyngby" appear to be based on the Magdalenian, during the Allerød and were closely associated with reindeer hunting.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Stellmoor was a seasonal settlement inhabited primarily during October, and bones from 650 reindeer have been found there.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] From Stellmoor there are also well-preserved arrow shafts of pine intended for the culture's characteristic *skaftunge* arrowheads of flint.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] A number of intact reindeer skeletons, with arrowheads in the chest, has been found, and they were probably sacrifices to higher powers.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] At the settlements, archaeologists have found circles of stone, which probably were the foundations of hide teepees.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The earliest reliable traces of habitation in the northern territories of Norway and western Sweden date to the transition period from the Younger Dryas to the Preboreal.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] More favourable living conditions, and past experience gained through seasonal rounds, prompted increased maritime resource exploitation in the northern territories.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] The Hensbacka group on the west coast of Sweden exemplifies the cultural fragmentation process that took place within the Continental Ahrensburgian.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] Instead of new immigrations at the beginning of the Mesolithic, the discovery of deposited bones and new dating indicate that there was no (significant) break in settlement continuity.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg-culture] New knowledge provides aspects for a further autochthonous development, with a rapid climatic change stimulating a swift cultural change.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Ahrensburg is situated in the *Tunneltal*, in which Alfred Rust excavated many items dating back to the ice age.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Ahrensburg is situated next to the Autobahn *A1* and on the railway route between the Hanseatic cities of Hamburg and Lübeck.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The Ahrensburger *Tunneltal* is a place of numerous excavations from the Upper Paleolithic culture.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The culture is called Ahrensburg culture by archaeologists.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The town dates back to the 13th Century, when the Counts of Schauenburg founded the village of Woldenhorn (which later became the town of Ahrensburg) and the neighbouring villages Ahrensfelde, Meilsdorf and Beimoor.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Woldenhorn is first mentioned in the year 1314.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The village came into the possession of the Cistercian Reinfeld Abbey in 1327, and Woldenhorn became the seat of the monastery reeve until the middle of the 16th century.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The "Arx Arnsburga", also called Arnesvelde castle, was built around the year 1200.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Ruins of the castle are still visible in the Hagen forest to the south of the town.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The town coat of arms shows the castle in the upper field.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] There are records of reeves based in the castle in 1295 and 1304.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] In 1326, Count John III of Schauenburg had his reeve relocated to Trittau and abandoned the castle.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] After the dissolution of the monasteries due to the Reformation, the whole area came into the possession of the king of Denmark.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] He rewarded his general Daniel Rantzau 1567 with lordship over these villages.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] His brother and heir Peter Rantzau built the Renaissance Ahrensburg Palace in the form of a water castle, now the symbol of the town, and the castle church around 1595.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The construction of almshouses directly by the church was exemplary.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The "Ahrensburg Estate" belonged to the so-called Noble Estates, which possessed a large amount of freedom and self-administration.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The Rantzaus' estate was heavily indebted by the middle of the 18th century and, in 1759, was acquired by the businessman Heinrich Carl von Schimmelmann.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Schimmelmann remodelled the castle and village in the baroque style and the current layout of the town reflects these plans.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] On 7 June 1867 the estate village Woldenhorn became an independent Prussian country community and renamed itself *Ahrensburg* after a decision by the community council.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] It belonged to the "Amt Ahrensburg", from which the "amtsfreie" community once more seceded in 1912.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The construction of the railway between Hamburg and Lübeck in the year 1865 made Ahrensburg a popular destination for outings outside Hamburg and the number of inhabitants increased.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] By 1910, the population had reached 2,750.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The incorporation of various surrounding communities in the year 1928 led to an increase in the town area to about 5 km2.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Building of the settlements "Daheim/Heimgarten" (partially on the territory of the current community of Ammersbek) and "Am Hagen" (originally called "Franz Seldte Settlement") commenced in 1933.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The rush of settlers from around Hamburg lead to the creation of the current housing layout.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] When Ahrensburg received city rights in 1949, the town had some 17,775 inhabitants – around half of which were refugees from the former eastern German regions.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Erica Keck, who was elected mayor in 1950, became the first female elected mayor in Germany.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The company Hela Gewürzwerk Hermann Laue moved its seat from Hamburg to Ahrensburg between 1989 and 1991.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] Ahrensburg was the seat of the Stormarn Provost of the Lutheran church from 1823 until 1899.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The town had a small Jewish community until the beginning of the 1930s.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The Synagogue was burnt down in the Kristallnacht in 1938 during the period of Nazism.
[src:ahrensburg-culture/ahrensburg] The Jewish cemetery (opened in 1822) can still be seen at the edge of town (Ahrensburg-West).
